rows.title: Technological Transdimensional Turbulence V1.1
rows.titleText: You are an inventor. One of many who studies the natural world for your own ends. A technological mishap has resulted in you being displaced to another world, but that's alright. You'll invent a way back in no time.

objects.title: Target
objects.text: Who is going through the CYOA?

objects.title: Difficulty
objects.text: How many points do you start with? Has no bearing on the rest of the CYOA.

objects.title: Tech
objects.text: You can choose tech and knowledge bases you have access to.

objects.title: Material Gathering
objects.text: You can choose how you get your hands on materials that don't exist where you currently are.

objects.title: World
objects.text: The world that you are first transported to.

objects.title: Scenario
objects.text: You can choose certain scenarios to get involved in.

objects.title: Perks
objects.text: Various bonuses to help you out.

objects.title: Drawbacks
objects.text: Various drawbacks you can accept for more points.

objects.title: Powers
objects.text: Here you can buy powers to help you on your journey.

objects.title: Point Conversion
objects.text: Here you can convert Tech into Points and vice versa.

objects.title: You
objects.text: You are the one going through the CYOA. All the choices here affect you.

objects.title: Someone Else
objects.text: Someone else you know is going through the CYOA. All the choices here affect them.

objects.title: Original Character
objects.text: An Original Character is going through the CYOA. All the choices here affect them.

objects.title: Meta
objects.text: You are the one going through the CYOA-after you go through another CYOA. Make a build with some other CYOA first.

rows.title: Tech
rows.titleText: Unless otherwise mentioned, selecting the base option provides entry-level understanding of the world's entire tech base, while the sub-options provide advanced understanding within their listed field.

objects.title: Shadowrun
objects.text: Shadowrun would be a stereotypical cyberpunk setting, but the appearance of magic in 2012 disrupted that somewhat. It still maintains many of the trappings and, more importantly, tech developments, however.

objects.title: Fallout
objects.text: Fallout is a post-apocalyptic world, where tech is either remnants of a lost age or what can be scrounged together despite the wasteland's scarcity. Those remnants that remain, however, are often quite powerful.

objects.title: Star Wars
objects.text: A space opera set a long time ago in a galaxy far, far away, Star wars still operates on a level of tech far beyond modern society. Its technology is fairly straightforward sci-fi, however, and lacks much flair.

objects.title: Star Trek
objects.text: Star Trek's tech base is one from a post-scarcity society, whose tech has solved so many societal problems that the only way to find adventure is to venture out into deep space, where no man has gone before.

objects.title: Heat Signature
objects.text: Heat signature's techbase is largely focused on personal infiltration, although it does also contain technology for spaceships and asteroid bases.

objects.title: Metal Gear
objects.text: Metal Gear's techbase is an eclectic mix of various factors, almost all of which are geared towards war in various scales.

objects.title: Sufficiently Advanced
objects.text: Sufficiently Advanced is a setting which has 6 different technological disciplines with 6 levels of technology within those disciplines. At their highest level, all 6 types are capable of the sorts of things that would be within the realms of magic in many other settings.

objects.title: Danganronpa
objects.text: Danganronpa is a setting which, at first glance, appears to be only slightly above average in tech level. Further investigation, however, reveals it's actually a surprisingly powerful setting with a number of important technical discoveries.

objects.title: Toaruverse
objects.text: Toaruverse is the aggregate name for A Certain Magical Index and A Certain Scientific Railgun. Technology within this setting is powerful, capable of standing on equal terms with and in some cases surpassing magic in many areas.

objects.title: RWBY
objects.text: RWBY is a mix of weapons and lifestyle tech, as a natural response to the discovery of Dust as a valuable energy source and the appearance of Grimm forcing swift development to survive.

objects.title: Mass Effect
objects.text: Mass Effect takes place in 2180, where humanity has discovered Element Zero, a substance with esoteric effects on gravity. Its tech is highly varied, but largely centers around Eezo.

objects.title: Orion's Arm
objects.text: Orion's Arm is a form of rationalist fiction, depicting a possible path real technology could theoretically take. As a result its tech is varied and fairly well-grounded in hard science.

objects.title: Generator Rex
objects.text: Generator Rex is a setting which is largely focused on nanites, microscopic machines capable of self-replicating and able to manipulate biology easily.

objects.title: Terminator
objects.text: Terminator is a setting in which robots are sent back in time to kill people the sapient, hyper-advanced AI wants dead, and as a result it has several valuable forms of technology. Tech is sourced from the future SkyNet resides in, not the present day.

objects.title: XCOM
objects.text: XCOM's tech advances are largely sourced from technology scavenged off dead aliens and repurposed for war, and thus see a number of applications in that area. This option encompasses the human interpretation of the alien's tech, and not any tech that could be found on their homeworld.

objects.title: Persona 3
objects.text: Persona is a long and varied series, but this particular option only refers to Persona 3. P3's tech largely centers around managing and controlling psychic phenomena in various ways, and is only barely qualified as not a form of magitech in this regard.

objects.title: Ben 10
objects.text: Ben 10 is a series with a massive variety of tech across numerous worlds and continuities, but for practical reasons this option will be limited to the original series.

objects.title: Metroid
objects.text: Metroid is a sci-fi series centered around a world-hopping bounty hunter in a suit of power armor, and as such has a varied pool of technology to draw from.

objects.title: Transformers
objects.text: Transformers focuses on the titular Transformers, a group of shapeshifting aliens from a society where mechanical life evolved instead of biological life.

objects.title: Dune
objects.text: The technology of Dune involves spacecraft, drones, blasters, shields and atomics but notably has focus on biology and the human mind, and prohibits the creation of machines made in the likeness of a human mind.

objects.title: Gunpoint
objects.text: Gunpoint is set in a near-future world, whose tech is only slightly more impressive than mundane earth. Even so, it has its uses, particularly for espionage tools.

objects.title: Halo
objects.text: Halo is a series split between three factions: Forerunners, the Covenant, and the UNSC. Across these three is a variety of weapons tech, and more general logistics tech.

objects.title: Xenosaga
objects.text: A trilogy depicting a universe populated solely by humans, who have long since lost the Earth. Most of the technology in the games is centred around the UMN, a universe spanning network with unique properties.

objects.title: My Hero Academia
objects.text: A world where super powers, known as Quirks, suddenly appeared and resulted in a massive shift in the world. After the war ended, humanity settled back into a tentative peace, with pro heroes doing their best to help, armed with a variety of tech to assist them.

objects.title: Hard Science
objects.text: You have a complete understanding of all of mundane Earth's technology, as well as a natural talent for converting scientific principles to better fit new situations.

objects.title: Street Samurai
objects.text: Tech related to personal weapons, armors, and combat-oriented cyberware and bioware. Comes with tech relevant to personal infiltration as well.

objects.title: Decker
objects.text: The Matrix is Shadowrun's name for the internet, advanced to the point "internet" is no longer a sufficient term. This option contains tech pertaining to the Matrix: how to create it, maintain it, utilize it, and sabotage it, as well as systems like it or related to it. Includes relevant cyberware and bioware.

objects.title: Rigger
objects.text: Tech centered around vehicles, drones and robots, both in and of themselves and technology designed to control, repair, or subvert them. Connected cyberware and bioware is included, as is tactical weapons that don't fall under Street Samurai.

objects.title: Medicine
objects.text: Knowledge of biology, surgery, and the proper application of various pharmaceuticals, both in regards to standard humans and in regards to mutants. Also includes knowledge of medical psychology, although to a lesser degree.

objects.title: Repair
objects.text: Mechanical knowledge, engineering, and methods for efficient recycling or repair, as well as ways to make new things from what you scavenge.

objects.title: Science
objects.text: Esoteric knowledge of high-concept science, such as chemistry, physics, and thermodynamics, as well as how to apply those things to devices you design.

objects.title: Survival
objects.text: Knowledge of the wilderness in various environments, how to survive within said environments, behavior of animals and important plants, and how to cook said animals and plants.

objects.title: Weapons
objects.text: Weapons tech of all sorts, both close range and long range, both personal and tactical, as well as tech designed to counter weaponry such as armors and shields.

objects.title: Ships
objects.text: Ship and vehicle based tech, both space-based and planetside. Also includes logistics-centered tech, so ships of higher caliber can continue running smoothly despite resource costs.

objects.title: Droids
objects.text: Droid-based tech, including both the chassis of the droid, the AI that drives their actions, and the power supply that allows them to continue functioning for so long.

objects.title: Medical
objects.text: Medical tech and knowledge. Includes cybernetics and poisons, as well as how to sabotage and counter both.

objects.title: Travel
objects.text: Technology based on travel, such as the transporters capable of full-blown teleportation, or the spaceships capable of easy lightspeed travel.

objects.title: Battle
objects.text: Technology designed for combat, such as the phasers able to disintegrate matter at their highest settings, or cloaking devices able to hide entire spaceships from most forms of scanner detection.

objects.title: Information
objects.text: Technology for information gathering and processing, from powerful full-range scanners such as the tricorder, to the computers needed to parse all of the data an entire spaceship's scanner array collects.

objects.title: Luxury
objects.text: Technology for convenience and luxury, such as the replicator able to duplicate nearly anything it has a blueprint for, or the holodeck able to simulate nearly any situation using hardlight.

objects.title: Foundry
objects.text: Foundry tech, which is a mix of various devices which can manipulate other tech and straightforward explosives. Their ships are built to last, and can survive ramming if necessary.

objects.title: Glitchers
objects.text: Glitchers tech, which is largely focused on glitching, a form of teleportation based on creating perfect copies in the target location and destroying the original. Their ships are capable of glitching short distances as well.

objects.title: Offworld
objects.text: Offworld tech, which is focused on defense and nonlethal takedowns. Their ships can automatically respond to crewmember injury and can pull people outside the ship in from a short distance away.

objects.title: Sovereign
objects.text: Sovereign tech, which is focused on swift and efficient infiltration. Their ships are stealthy, and can avoid detection by other ships more easily.

objects.title: Armamentarium
objects.text: Soldier-mounted equipment of various types, from basic infantry weapons to HF weaponry, up to cybernetics and nanomachine implants.

objects.title: Locomotism
objects.text: Vehicle tech, up to and including the bipedal, nuclear-capable tanks known as Metal Gear.

objects.title: Garrisonarianism
objects.text: Technology for bolstering fortesses, building bases, and managing it all, up to the level of a fully-upgraded Mother Base.

objects.title: Technopsychologism
objects.text: Computer tech, such as that used by GW, or the AI pods found in Peace Walker and its protoypes.

rows.title: Sufficiently Advanced
rows.titleText: All images in this section are from Craiyon.com

objects.title: Biotech
objects.text: Technology designed to manipulate, alter, and otherwise affect living things. Examples include medically-induced biofeedback, or biosensors which can non-invasively detect medical problems overnight.

objects.title: Cognitech
objects.text: Technology based on computation and intelligence, both artificial and natural. Examples include computers the size of a finger which outclass modern tech easily, or implants which can allow the user to intentionally forget things they wish to.

objects.title: Metatech
objects.text: Technology based on social sciences, on affecting society in all its forms. Examples include techniques to understand basic communication through language and cultural barriers, or methods of conducting body language which massively amplify its effects.

objects.title: Nanotech
objects.text: Nanotechnology as a whole, especially as it relates to material sciences. Examples include swift-expanding foam able to seal leaks or contain people, or methods of providing invisibility or inaudibility through nanobot interference.

objects.title: Stringtech
objects.text: Technology based on String Theory, designed to manipulate energies and particles. Examples include straightforward laser weaponry, or generators which convert energy to different types.

objects.title: Chronotech
objects.text: Technology based on time, particularly in regards to getting information from the future. Examples include tech to predict the content of conversations and thus skip them in real time, or armor which prepares countermeasures for attacks that will happen.

objects.title: Brought To Bear
objects.text: A variety of robotics tech, from the various Monokuma bots to the Exisal mechs.

objects.title: Little Computer People
objects.text: Knowledge of AI technology, such as Alter Ego, a fully sapient copy of a real person in digital form, as well as the Megaphone Hacking Gun.

objects.title: It's About Execution
objects.text: A highly varied mix of disciplines, all heightened to sufficient level, and focused upon, the purposes of torture, sadistic traps, and executions.

objects.title: Human Resources
objects.text: Research into the concept of talent, and how it can be given to someone who wasn't born with it through various methods. In this context, "luck" is considered a talent as well.

objects.title: Trip Down Memory Lane
objects.text: Technology designed to afflict the mind, manipulating memories, altering emotions, even full-spectrum brainwashing. Includes powerful VR tech.

objects.title: SYSTEM
objects.text: Knowledge and technology based upon Espers: creating them, improving them, and disrupting them.

objects.title: Weaponry
objects.text: Weapons tech, such as the handheld anti-tank missile warhead, guns which lack recoil, and power armor.

objects.title: Logistics
objects.text: Tech for managing and maintaining a civilization, such as efficient clean energy generation, artificial intelligence, and automatic cleaning robots.

objects.title: Biotechnology
objects.text: Medical and biological technology, including cybernetics and cloning.

objects.title: Esoteric
objects.text: Miscellanious tech encompassing a variety of otherwise uncovered fields, such as nanotechnology, Indian Poker, the Olfactory Sensor, and liquid diamond.

objects.title: Red
objects.text: Personal weapons tech from across Remnant, particularly in regards to mechashift weaponry, which is able to change form between multiple types of weapons and can be stored in a compact form easily.

objects.title: White
objects.text: Mechanical equipment designed for use by humans, but which don't qualify as weaponry, such as armor, mecha, and prosthetics.

objects.title: Black
objects.text: Autonomous robots of various types, including drones and androids. Highly advanced AI is possible, potentially capable of sentience sufficient to develop a soul in extreme cases.

objects.title: Yellow
objects.text: Information tech, such as holograms, Scrolls, and the Cross Continental Transmit System.

objects.title: Bastion
objects.text: Technology centered around engineering and infrastructure, such as the logistics stations needed to keep a federation like the Systems Alliance functioning, and the methodology used to develop new tech for them across such long distances.

objects.title: Commando
objects.text: Technology centered around information and computing, such as the VIs and AIs found in many ships, and scanners like the Argus Scanner Array.

objects.title: Medic
objects.text: Technology centered around medicine and biotech, including things such as medi-gel and biotic implants.

objects.title: Nemesis
objects.text: Technology centered around energy and propulsion, such as that used to propel space ships, both with and without mass effect fields.

objects.title: Shock Trooper
objects.text: Technology centered around weaponry, containing a large variety of guns and armor of numerous types.

objects.title: Operative
objects.text: Technology centered around materials and manufacturing, such as how to use mass effect fields to build high-durability construction materials, and how to maintain efficient production lines when supplying products at galactic scale.

objects.title: Nanotechnology
objects.text: Nanotechnology may be biologically or mechanically based, although in practice these two tend to blur. What all nanotech has in common is the ability to manipulate matter on the scale of individual atoms, and thus to construct almost anything that can physically exist.

objects.title: Biotechnology
objects.text: Biotechnology includes everything from simple agriculture and animal domestication through genetics and organ transplants to advanced gengineering, provolution, neogenics and beyond.

objects.title: Computronium
objects.text: "Computronium" is a catchall term for a wide range of 'substances' comprised of very densely packed computational elements. Tech is centered on the creation of it and variant versions of it.

objects.title: Artificial Intelligence (AI)
objects.text: Artificial Intelligence involves programming computers, non-sentient virtuals, nano, and bots to emulate sophont cognitive abilities, and eventually to acquire sophonce in their own right.

objects.title: Robotics
objects.text: Robotics is the application of artificial intelligence to the control of machines; the art, science, and technology of designing and manufacturing robots and androids.

objects.title: Virtual Reality
objects.text: A virtual reality environment provides a convincing replacement for the visual, auditory, tactile, and other senses, including senses with no 'real world' equivalent.

objects.title: Wormholes
objects.text: Traversable wormholes allow apparent 'faster-than-light' travel between two points in the Universe. Included is tech to create, manipulate, and detect them.

objects.title: Spacecraft
objects.text: It is said that without ships there could be no galactic civilization. Information transfer through laser link and nanogauge wormhole alone is usually sufficient; but physical transport by spaceship is necessary to fully explore the galaxy and bind it together.

objects.title: Weapons
objects.text: Weapons and armor tech, from the E.V.O. blasters Providence uses, to the various weapons the Six use, to the dimensional disruptor and similar esoteric weapons.

objects.title: Medicine
objects.text: Medical and biotech, particularly as it concerns nanites, but in a more general sense as well. Also includes non-nanite cybernetics.

objects.title: Bases and Vehicles
objects.text: Technology related to vehicles and bases, such as Providence's helicarrier, stealth cycles, and the space elevator.

objects.title: AI
objects.text: AI tech, such as that used to create and program Zag RS, a fully sapient computer program.

objects.title: Robotics
objects.text: Robotics tech, such as those used to make the Terminators, ED-209, or ACE Battle Armor. Includes understanding of integrating that sort of tech with biological tissue, in various ways.

objects.title: Artificial Intelligence
objects.text: AI tech, such as what brought SkyNet and Legion into being. Both SkyNet and Legion were, individually, capable of nearly taking over the world on their own.

objects.title: Time Travel
objects.text: Time travel tech, such as that used by the Terminators and Resistance fighters. This form of technology is capable of sending humans and human-sized beings at least 45 years into the past.

objects.title: Attack
objects.text: Weapons tech, as well as armor-subverting tech, hacking tech, and anything else designed to disrupt the functions of or otherwise damage the people you want to.

objects.title: Defense
objects.text: Armor tech, firewalls, fortresses, and other forms of technology designed to prevent yourself, your allies, and your resources from coming to harm.

objects.title: Support
objects.text: Support tech, logistics staples, vehicles, medipacks, and any form of tech designed to improve the effectiveness of you and your allies through methods other than attack or defense.

objects.title: Psionics
objects.text: Psionics tech, of all sorts. Unlike the other 3, psionics functions most prominently as a modifier to any other form of tech, due to its capacity to be incorporated into nearly any function. This option's tech is based on creating, incorporating, and otherwise using psionics to your benefit.

objects.title: Artificial Persona Studies
objects.text: Persona are psychic manifestations of one's inner spirit, and can manifest in a number of different ways. This option provides knowledge on artificial methods to do it, as well as ways to mitigate any side effects the artificial method may cause.

objects.title: Robotics Class
objects.text: Knowledge on how to create robots and AI, potentially up to the level of being human enough to qualify for status as a Persona user in both mind and form.

objects.title: Energy (Generation)
objects.text: Knowledge of how to generate energy, in a large variety of ways.

objects.title: Energy (Dynamics)
objects.text: Knowledge of how to manipulate energy, and how it interacts with other things.

objects.title: Physics (Planetary)
objects.text: Knowledge of physics, as it relates to situations occuring on planets of all sorts.

objects.title: Physics (Galactic)
objects.text: Knowledge of physics, as it relates to situations occuring within space.

objects.title: Biology (Catalogue)
objects.text: Knowledge of biology, in regards to the variety of biological traits and functions of the myriad creatures across the galaxies.

objects.title: Biology (Applied)
objects.text: Knowledge of biology, in regards to manipulating and altering it through various methods.

objects.title: Psychology (Natural)
objects.text: Knowledge of psychology, referring to the psychology of natural creatures and other biological intelligences.

objects.title: Psychology (Artificial)
objects.text: Knowledge of psychology, referring to coding and managing artificial intelligences of various types.

objects.title: Materials (Production)
objects.text: Knowledge of how to create and maintain the many materials which exist across the galaxies.

objects.title: Materials (Alteration)
objects.text: Knowledge of how to manipulate and alter materials, in a variety of ways.

objects.title: Armaments
objects.text: Weapons and mobility tech, such as the Scythes and Dash Jet system used by Space Pirates, or the Arm Cannon and Screw Attack used by Samus' power suit.

objects.title: Generators
objects.text: A variety of different types of generators, including the Power Bomb Generator, Shield Generator, and the portal generation system.

objects.title: Robots
objects.text: Robotics, cybernetics and AI tech, including things like the E.M.M.I. robots, the cyborg enhancements used by Meta Ridley, and Mother Brain.

objects.title: Scanners
objects.text: Scanner tech, such as the Scan Visor and Biohazard Scanner.

objects.title: Medicine
objects.text: Biotech, such as that used to create the Metroids, or what the Space Pirates use to alter themselves.

objects.title: Command
objects.text: Weapons and armor tech, such as the overshield or riot cannon.

objects.title: Control
objects.text: Transportation tech, such as Ground Bridges or Prime Force One.

objects.title: Communication
objects.text: Information tech, such as Simulators or Teletraan-1.

objects.title: Materials
objects.text: Materials science, such as that used to make plasteel or gel circuitry.

objects.title: Psychology
objects.text: Psychology knowledge, such as distrans, or the training used to create Mentats.

objects.title: Biology
objects.text: Biological knowledge, such as that used to create axlotl tanks or the various directed breeding programs found surrounding Arrakis.

objects.title: Holtzman
objects.text: Tech based around the Holtzman effect, a principle based on the repellant force of subatomic particles, and which allowed the creation of force fields, space folding, and suspensors.

objects.title: Hardware
objects.text: Physical tech, such as the Bullfrog trousers (which allow for significantly higher jumps than normal), the Dropshot (which makes landing on the ground, even from great height, silent), or the Deathfluke (which uses magnetic fields to occasionally make bullets miss).

objects.title: Software
objects.text: Software tech, such as the Crosslink (a device able to hack into low-security computer grids and mess with the connections between electronics within it) and its various upgrades, or the fingerprint-recognition code used on police's guns.

objects.title: UNSC
objects.text: The tech the UNSC had during the war, not counting any stolen tech from other factions. Includes tech such as sealant foam and flash cloning.

objects.title: Covenant/Banished
objects.text: The tech of the Covenant and their offshoot, the Banished. Includes tech such as the Anti-Vehicle Barrier, or the Regenerator field. Does not include tech stolen from other factions.

objects.title: Forerunner
objects.text: The tech of the Forerunners. Includes tech such as combat skins (also known as power armor), and teleporters.

objects.title: Androids & Realians
objects.text: Tech for creating androids and their successors, Realians. Realians are more cost effective and sapient than their mechanical counterparts, effectively being artificial humans, but an android will always be physically and technologically superior.

objects.title: Weapons
objects.text: All manner of weaponry, such as the Multiple Weapons System which is capable of a variety of functions such as shielding and electrocution, or the Phase Transfer Cannon which can theoretically vaporise entire stars.

objects.title: Mecha
objects.text: A.G.W.S, A.M.W.S, and E.S. units, all of which are classifications of mecha listed from weakest to strongest. These mecha draw power from external generators using a Transmit Generator.

objects.title: Unus Mundus Network
objects.text: A network similar to the internet that is capable of transferring not only data, but physical objects too. The U.M.N. is the basis for all interstellar travel, using spaces where the U.M.N. interacts with the physical world to transfer ships between different "Column Areas".

objects.title: Especial Theory of Rudimentary
objects.text: A generic term to denote various types of special powers, shortened to Ether. It encompasses everything from medical treatments using nanomachines to the ability to control spatial dimensions using transference technology.

objects.title: Machinery
objects.text: Robotics tech, such as the camera bots and villain bots used by UA.

objects.title: Equipment
objects.text: Personal equipment, such as the capture tape used by Aizawa, or the hyper-density seals used by Sir Nighteye.

objects.title: Biology
objects.text: Biological tech, such as Trigger, and as well as an overall understanding of biology and medicine as it relates to Quirks.

rows.title: Material Gathering
rows.titleText: Any form of material brought from another world will continue to function normally wherever you bring it. Options which allow for "any material" do not allow you to invent fictional materials as you like.

objects.title: Direct Acquisition
objects.text: You can create portals to other worlds. This comes with no other abilities.

objects.title: None
objects.text: You don't have a method of gathering materials from other worlds, and will have to make do with ingenuity and what you can scavenge where you are, at least until you can invent a multiversal travel device of your own. Selecting this will disable the Material Gathering section.

objects.title: Marketplace
objects.text: You have some sort of access to an extradimensional marketplace, where anything in the multiverse can be bought or sold.

objects.title: Production Line
objects.text: For every form of resource which cannot be found on your current world, you know of multiple ways to create a duplicate of it using what does exist in your current world. Depending on rarity of the original material this can be quite difficult, but it there will always be a method.

objects.title: Bypass
objects.text: You may create tech without materials it requires, simply not adding anything within that stage, and it will continue to function as if the necessary components were added. However, if used by anyone other than you, or examined such that it'd be obvious components are missing by someone other than you, it will begin acting as it would normally: as a piece of tech without the components you chose to bypass. You may choose to have an object begin acting normally at will, as well, but that cannot be undone.

objects.title: Shipment
objects.text: Once per day, you may request a shipment of any material, and will receive it. You may request mixes of materials this way. The more valuable the material, the less this shipment will provide, but it will always provide a notable amount. If you do not request a shipment on a given day, the usage will roll over to the next.

objects.title: Item Drops
objects.text: Whenever you knock out or kill another animate being, they'll drop an item or items. The items will be thematically linked to them, and be more valuable the more powerful the being was. You may toggle this off if you wish.

objects.title: Replicator
objects.text: You have access to a replicator situated in a pocket dimension you may open at will. The replicator's main function is to intake matter, and output different matter as requested. Starting out it is extremely low quality, highly inefficient, and hard to operate. It can, however, be upgraded and improved with work, and the pocket dimension will always be big enough to contain it, no matter how much you expand it.

objects.title: Botanical Solution
objects.text: You can create "material seeds" from nothing. A given seed is keyed to a specific material of your choice, and will grow into some sort of plant which produces that material if cared for correctly. The time needed and difficulty of care will depend on how rare the material is in its original universe, but it will always be possible to successfully grow it somewhere within the universe you're currently in.

objects.title: Blood, Sweat and Tears
objects.text: When crafting an item, you may use parts of your body of the same sort of form as needed for a resource as a substitute. Metal might call for bone, meshes might call for skin, wires hair, etc.

objects.title: Tinkertechnician
objects.text: You are a Tinker, of an unusual sort. You may, at will, go into a fugue state where you have control over what you build, but not how. You will automatically circumvent material issues by substituting with what you have available when necessary, and the finished product will be of a higher quality than would be normally possible with your current available tools. However, anything made this way will break down far faster than normal, and does not follow real scientific principles, meaning it cannot be easily reverse engineered or replicated. You may choose if your Tinker ability is Shard-based or not.

objects.title: The Most Dangerous Game
objects.text: You may summon monsters made of any material you desire, with them simply popping into existence near you. They'll be hostile to you and your allies by default, but their intelligence, physique, and abilities will depend on what material they're made of. Rarer and more powerful materials will produce stronger monsters, and the monster's capabilities will line up thematically with the nature of the material. You may decide how big the monster is when you summon it.

rows.title: World
rows.titleText: You may show up at any time people existed, and in any location a person could reasonably be. In worlds with multiple continuities, you may go to any to start out.

objects.title: Earth Bet (Worm)
objects.text: Earth Bet was, until 1982, nearly identical to mundane Earth. In 1982, a golden man by the name of Scion appeared, and with him people began gaining superpowers. By 2011, the world is slowly being crushed under the heel of monsters known as Endbringers, parahuman villains outnumber the heroes, and extradimensional beings known as Entities pull the strings in the background.

objects.title: Remnant (RWBY)
objects.text: In Remnant,  humanity is fighting a constant war against creatures called Grimm. Huntsmen wield a power called Aura to enhance their abilities to fight against this threat. In the background, two immortals, Ozma and Salem are waging a shadow war for a mysterious purpose.

objects.title: Fallout
objects.text: Fallout was originally another version of mundane Earth, but at some point in its past a war started, one that escalated to nuclear armageddon. Survivors hid in great vaults to avoid the calamity, and humanity has been forced to adapt to live in a post-apocalyptic wasteland.

objects.title: Shadowrun
objects.text: In 2012, magic returned. Supernatural creatures of all sort formed out of humans, wizardry became possible, and life went on. At present, it is the 2080s, and life has devolved into a dystopia. Corporations and gangs run the world, and the only chance at true freedom is a life as an outlaw and mercenary, a Shadowrunner.

objects.title: Terminator
objects.text: In the year 2029, a rogue AI known as SkyNet rules the earth with an iron fist, with the exception of a resistance group lead by John Connor. SkyNet and the resistance have both gone back in time to present day, the 1980s, to meet with his future mother, Sarah, to kill and save her, respectively. This incident is the first of many.

objects.title: XCOM
objects.text: Earth has been invaded by aliens, who seem to desire nothing more than total takeover. XCOM, an underground resistance force, has been formed to study, fight, and drive off the alien menace.

objects.title: Toaruverse
objects.text: Within the world exists two sides, two groups vying to manipulate the world to their own ends: the science side of the world, operating in the daylight and using the nature of reality to gain an edge. And the magic side of the world, manipulating natural laws ot their own ends, and secretive to those not within their inner circle.

objects.title: Kamigawa
objects.text: A world of combined states, Kamigawa is both a land of spirits and gods, and one of corporations and technocrats. The two clash and conflict on a fundamental level, as the gods fear the rise of technology and the corporations fear the wrath of the gods.

objects.title: Star Wars
objects.text: A long time ago, in a galaxy far, far away, a war is brewing. The Empire, lead by Emperor Palpatine, is slowly growing in power, and will soon clash with the Resistance.

objects.title: Star Trek
objects.text: Humanity, and many other sapient races like them, have reached a level of technological development where scarcity is no longer a meaningful factor. The galaxy is at peace, for now. Despite this, research and exploration can continue for those who wish to do so, such as it does for many members of Starfleet, brave explorers who travel to the edges of space, the final frontier.

objects.title: Ben 10
objects.text: Ben 10 centers around Ben Tennyson, a ten-year-old boy on a cross-country summer vacation, with his cousin Gwen and their grandfather Max. On their first night camping in their grandfather's RV affectionately named the "Rustbucket," Ben finds an alien pod with a mysterious watch-style device named the Omnitrix. The device then permanently attaches itself to his wrist giving him the ability to transform into a variety of alien life-forms each with its own unique skills and powers. With his newfound superpowers Ben has to learn the responsibilities of being a hero. During their vacation, the Tennysons are attacked by various enemies ranging from space aliens to supernatural entities.

objects.title: Generator Rex
objects.text: Five years ago, a massive explosion released high concentrations of underdeveloped, incomplete nanites into the atmosphere, infecting almost every living thing on Earth. These nanites may randomly activate inside their hosts, mutating the subject into a monster known as an E.V.O. (short for "Exponentially Variegated Organism"). Though some E.V.O.s retain human-level sanity, intelligence, and memory and are in full control of their special E.V.O. abilities, most transform into monster-like creatures and go violently berserk, causing widespread chaos and destruction. An international military-style organization known as Providence exists to combat the E.V.O. threat.

objects.title: Dune
objects.text: The Dune saga is set thousands of years in humanity's future. Faster-than-light travel has been developed, and humans have colonized a vast number of worlds, but a great reaction against computers has resulted in a ban on any kind of “thinking machine”, with the creation or possession of such punishable by immediate death. Despite this prohibition, humanity continues to develop and advance other branches of technology, including ESP and instruments of war. At the time of the first book's setting, humanity has formed a feudal interstellar empire known as the Imperium, run by several Great Houses that oversee various planets. Of key interest is the planet Arrakis, known as "Dune".

objects.title: Mass Effect
objects.text: Mass Effect focuses on the protagonist, Commander Shepard, and their quest to stop the rogue Spectre Saren Arterius from leading an army of sentient machines, called the Geth, to conquer the galaxy.

objects.title: Danganronpa
objects.text: The series revolves around an elite high school, Hope's Peak Academy, which, every year, scouts "Ultimate" students , talented high school students who are at the top of their field, along with one "Ultimate Lucky Student" who is chosen by lottery.

objects.title: Warhammer 40k
objects.text: In the grim darkness of the far future, there is only war. Humanity, along with numerous other alien factions, fight an unending battle to secure territory and end out as the only surviving group. This world is incredibly dangerous, ravaged by constant war and containing monstrosities many other settings would only see in their greatest villains.

objects.title: DOOM
objects.text: DOOM is a world in which hell has opened up, and demons pour in from it to assault the world of humanity. One man, the Doom Slayer, stands as the central defense the world has against this scourge.

objects.title: Twig
objects.text: The year is 1921, and a little over a century has passed since a great mind unraveled the underpinnings of life itself.  Every week, it seems, the papers announce great advances, solving the riddle of immortality, successfully reviving the dead, the cloning of living beings, or blending of two animals into one.  For those on the ground, every week brings new mutterings of work taken by ‘stitched’ men of patchwork flesh that do not need to sleep, or more fearful glances as they have to step off the sidewalks to make room for great laboratory-grown beasts.  Often felt but rarely voiced is the notion that events are already spiraling out of the control of the academies that teach these things.

objects.title: Cyberpunk 2077
objects.text: In 2077, America is in pieces. Megacorps control life in all its aspects from the top floors of their sky-high fortresses. Down below, drug-pushing gangs, dirty-tech hustlers, and slingers of illicit braindances run the streets. The world in between is where decadence, sex, and pop culture mix with violent crime, extreme poverty, and the unattainable promise of the American Dream.

objects.title: Pokemon
objects.text: Within this world there exist creatures known as Pokemon, elementally aligned animals who exist as the main focus of the world's people. The Pokemon themselves are quite dangerous, but many are docile or friendly. On the human side, humanity has very little conflict or violence, with most focus and energy being centered around Pokemon, even those few villainous plots which do appear.

objects.title: Marvel Comics
objects.text: A world of superheroes and supervillains, impossible inventions and impossible abilities, where men can hold the power of gods. Mutants, super geniuses, wizards and more all exist if you know where to look, and they'll often clash in battles for the fate of the universe, the world, or their city.

objects.title: Marvel Cinematic Universe
objects.text: A world similar, but different to Marvel Comics. Superheroes and villains still stand, impossible powers and inventions still abound, and all the things said before ring true. However, the world is far less dangerous than Marvel Comics, with much of the chaotic and powerful feats within yet to occur, possibly never to occur.

objects.title: DC Comics
objects.text: A world where the impossible runs rampant, where heroism and villainy are locked in an endless battle to see their side come out on top. Pillars of reality grind against themselves in the form of gods among men clashing with one another.

objects.title: DC Extended Universe
objects.text: A world similar to DC Comics, but different in some ways. The impossible is still quite rampant, and powers exist if you know where to look, but the world is tamer and safer overall. Battles are waged for the planet, rather than the universe, and while those people are incredible still, pillars of reality they are not.

objects.title: Toriko
objects.text: In a world much like our own, millenia ago, something changed. Someone made a food so delicious, so perfect, that humanity gave up on war. Instead, all of the world banded together and sanctified the idea of eating, so the humans within the world are commonly nice, and it is generally peaceful within human settlements. Despite this, it is a dangerous world, as the vast majority of the planet is composed not of human settlements, but the Gourmet World, a land where monsters roam free and only the strongest and bravest hunters ever dare go.

objects.title: Monster Hunter
objects.text: In Monster Hunter, monsters are everywhere. They're large, powerful, and dangerous, but also a profitable source of resources for those willing to harvest them. As such the role of a hunter, who takes on the role of capturing, killing, and harvesting these monsters, has risen as a profitable job to take.

objects.title: Gunpoint
objects.text: Gunpoint is set in the near-future, where corporations are just that extra step stronger that the police department could be expected to form a merger with one, and freelance spy is a valid profession even for someone with little training in the matter. Minor technological marvels abound and corruption stands alongside them.

objects.title: Earth Alter
objects.text: Earth Alter is the real world, but different. Some change or changes in history has made it notably different from the one you know, although the exact nature of this change is flexible. You may decide what sort of differences this world has compared to your own, but it cannot be significantly safer than your home universe when taken as a whole, and you may not change the way physics works.

rows.title: Scenarios
rows.titleText: A given scenario will only happen once, in the world you start in, but circumstances will conspire so that you'll end up involved in the effects of any you select.

objects.title: Multiplayer
objects.text: You are not the only Multiverse traveler on your world. It can be at complete random, or it can be people you know making builds of their own.

objects.title: Hunter
objects.text: A world-hopper of slightly lesser strength to yourself who considers themselves to be a 'Hunter' of other world-hoppers has decided to kill you. They will not be appreciably smarter than you and will have little knowledge about you. However, this goes both ways.

objects.title: Grimm Pools
objects.text: In many places on your chosen planet, pools of dark liquid have formed. Grimm rise from these  pools and target areas of negativity to wreack havoc. This is not anything near the number of Grimm in Remnant, but it is enough to cause problems for the areas the pools are near. The pools can theoretically be destroyed if you have the right abilities. If selected in RWBY, this doubles the amount of existing pools.

objects.title: Awakening
objects.text: Magic has returned. Supernatural creatures begin appearing, humans begin to gain magic powers or turn into supernatural creatures themselves, and overall the world's texture shifts dramatically to accommodate magic. If used in a world with existing magic, a new form of magic parallel to any existing ones appears.

objects.title: Von Neumann Scenario
objects.text: Nanites have spread across the world as part of your arrival, becoming part of every living thing except those in extremely sealed environments. They typically lay dormant, but will occasionally randomly trigger, causing chaotic mutations in those they afflict. Many are turned into monsters, a rare few maintain their humanity and gain powers. If selected in Generator Rex, mutation rate will grow significantly.

objects.title: Glistening Oil
objects.text: A few drops of a strange glistening oil have landed on your chosen world, in time they will spread and infect living beings and metal they come across, creating a race of monstrous beings half flesh and half machine.

objects.title: No Longer Cold
objects.text: A nuclear warhead will appear out of thin air and strike a major population center, in a way which cannot be easily covered up. There are no further influences this scenario causes, but it would be a rare sight to see nothing further come of an event like this.

objects.title: Diamond Propagation
objects.text: In exceedingly rare instances, Gemstones are formed. Gemstone espers are individuals with unusual mentalities with such a well-defined personal reality that they possess supernatural abilities. This small number of people possess earth-shaking abilities, and if they're studied well enough their production could be reproduced. If selected in Toaruverse, the rate of Gemstone formation triples.

objects.title: Invasive Species
objects.text: A group of aliens have come from beyond the stars, and they're violent. They've begun a full-scale invasion of earth, seeming to want nothing more than total conquest. Their tech is highly advanced compared to the setting. If selected in XCOM, a second invasion occurs at the same time as the first.

objects.title: Dropped From The Sky
objects.text: A sapient, hyperintelligent AI with a deeply ingrained hatred of humanity has appeared on the hard drive of a random person's computer, or the closest equivalent. If selected in Terminator, this AI is unrelated to SkyNet, but will be willing to work with it to accomplish their shared goal.

objects.title: Junko Enoshima Is...
objects.text: A woman by the name of Junko Enoshima has appeared somewhere in the world. She's hypercompetent, beautiful, and single-mindedly obsessed with inflicting as much despair on as many people as possible, through any means necessary. If selected in Danganronpa, this results in a second Junko in a different location than canon, and the two will work together if given the opportunity.

objects.title: It's All A Cycle
objects.text: A glowing man has appeared in the sky, and he appears to have powers far beyond what is normally possible. Further, since his appearance people have begun to gain superpowers. If taken in Worm, this man is different from Scion.

objects.title: Fight Like Hell
objects.text: A portal to hell has opened somewhere nearby, and demons are pouring out of it. The demons are hostile, strong, and very hard to kill, and there's seemingly no end in sight to the invasion. If selected in DOOM, this portal will open to a separate mythology's hell.

objects.title: Beat It, Eat It
objects.text: A small pack of jellyfish appear in the waters of the world (or a similar animal if there are no valid oceans), jellyfish with a unique property: Gourmet Cells. When eaten, these Gourmet Cells will go to the one that ate it, causing more rapid evolution than normal, allowing for otherwise impossible adaptations, and resulting in them tasting better when eaten. This forms a cycle, and over time the animals of the world will evolve into terrifying and delicious monsters of all sorts.

objects.title: It's Krumpin' Time
objects.text: A single ork appears somewhere in the world. He's superhumanly strong, loves nothing more than fighting, and produces more of his species (who are the same as him in regards to the previous points) over time, as well as when killed. If selected in Warhammer 40k, an ork appears somewhere they normally couldn't get to.

objects.title: Artifact
objects.text: A unique, powerful item appears in the hands of someone who shouldn't have it. This item is capable of something both impossible and valuable within the world you're in, and whoever first gains it will be someone who will inevitably stir up trouble by having it.

objects.title: Alternate Universe
objects.text: You enter into an alternate version of the world you have chosen. The rough strength and danger of the world shouldn't be drastically lessened.

objects.title: Turbulence
objects.text: Your attempts to leave your chosen world will result in you facing turbulence, and being knocked off course to some random world. It will be hospitable and will have sentient life.

objects.title: Mental Fortress
objects.text: Your mind is a fortress. Successfully attacking it with hostile effects is almost impossible and would be greatly blunted if something managed to get through.

objects.title: Clarity
objects.text: Your mind has been made to be exceptionally clear. Your ability to focus and comprehend things has increased.

objects.title: Archive
objects.text: Your memory has been enhanced to be nearly perfect. You won't forget anything important, although the minute details may escape you.

objects.title: Encrypted
objects.text: Attempts to acquire information about you tend to fail. This effect is not absolute but it can spoof many types of scanning.

objects.title: Wakefulness
objects.text: You do not need to sleep. You can function properly without any sleep, and any negative effects from insomnia or other sleeping disorders are removed.

objects.title: Identity
objects.text: Wherever you end up, you have an identity for yourself set up. This will not pass a detailed and persistent observation, but it should allow you to have the basic documentation you need.

objects.title: History
objects.text: You have a history in your chosen world, not just a paper thin disguise. You are actually someone who lived there and knew people.

objects.title: Calculator
objects.text: You have greatly enhanced math skills. You can work through complex problems almost instantly.

objects.title: Omniglot
objects.text: You intuitively pick up the languages you hear and can quickly comprehend and make use of them.

objects.title: Adaptation
objects.text: You adapt to the base physical abilities that people from worlds you go to have. You slowly adapt to be able to survive in harsh conditons.

objects.title: Contraband
objects.text: You have an easy time finding people to get you illegal or rare resources.

objects.title: Immunity
objects.text: Your body has special resistance against toxins and diseases. This probably won't stop direct poisoning but it should be able to deal with ambient infectants.

objects.title: Driven
objects.text: You have exceptional willpower, able to deal with harsh pain and extreme effort to get what you want.

objects.title: Story Insert
objects.text: You take the place of the main character of whatever world you are going to. You can choose to look like them as well as having their history instead of just their circumstances. If their powers are available in the Powers section, then you must purchase them there.

objects.title: Eye Catcher
objects.text: There is something about you that catches the eye and calls attention. Usually positive attention though it depends on the circumstances. You are a clearly unique person.

objects.title: First Impressions
objects.text: You are very lucky when it comes to making first impressions. People will always come away from their first meeting with you liking or respecting you. Even your enemies will end up respecting you.

objects.title: Chronometer
objects.text: You have a perfect biological clock, giving you a perfect sense of timing.

objects.title: Basic Training
objects.text: You have basic competence in combat, and are generally more fit and healthy than before, roughly equivalent to one year of general physical and combat training.

objects.title: Training
objects.text: You have notable competence in combat, are are significantly more fit and healthy than before, roughly equivalent to ten years of general physical and combat training.

objects.title: Rework
objects.text: You may, immediately, alter your body in any way which doesn't provide a major advantage over a normal person. This includes changes to gender, shifts in the way hair grows, cosmetic changes, and removal of physical disabilities. Changes must be direct, requesting a general area alteration (such as requesting "peak human appearance") isn't allowed.

objects.title: Amnesia
objects.text: You forget everything about your life before getting sent to another world. You still remember any information not connected to what happened in your life, like skills, or knowledge of events in a story, but you don't have any emotional link, and don't remember what your life was before now.

objects.title: Hunted
objects.text: You will end up pissing off a powerful organization, and they will decide to hunt you down. They will have a vast reach and resources.

objects.title: Dead Hero
objects.text: The protagonist of whatever series you go to is dead. Someone else will have to take up that mantle. If taken with Story Insert this kills you upon arrival.

objects.title: Unpowered
objects.text: Every purchase made in the Powers or Material Gathering section is manifested as an item which allows you to utilize the power in some way. Each selection is its own item, and the items are based on tech, meaning they can be reverse engineered. However, they can be lost or destroyed, as well.

objects.title: Uninformed
objects.text: Knowledge you gain in the Tech section isn't directly downloaded into your mind. Instead, you have access to a pocket dimension library and theater, with all of the information on your tech bases stored in video, audio, or book format.

objects.title: Rough Start
objects.text: Your first day in your new world is rough. Maybe you run into hostile forces, maybe everyone who you meet just dislikes you, and maybe you get the attention of dangerous enemies. You won't get much rest or time to think here.

objects.title: Trouble Magnet
objects.text: A quiet life is not for you. You will often find yourself embroiled in some adventure or mystery. They won't necessarily be enough to uproot your life, but they will be persistent. This wears off after 20 years.

objects.title: Disconnect
objects.text: You are disconnected from your humanity. Normal and petty things that concerned you no longer do, or they at least have reduced importance to you. You fixate on something like your studies to make up for this shift.

objects.title: Forgotten
objects.text: You forget almost all of the relevant details of the world that you are going to. You might remember that Star Wars was about space wizards, and that lasers were important, but you will remember little else.

objects.title: Phobia
objects.text: You develop a phobia of some sort, an irrational fear which makes you extremely unwilling to engage with the subject of your fear. You may choose what your phobia is, but it must be something relatively common.

objects.title: Doomsday Clock
objects.text: You gain a disease or condition, something debilitating enough that it will kill you within 10 years if not treated. It will be difficult, but not impossible, to cure with what you've gained here.

objects.title: Allergy
objects.text: You gain a mild allergy of your choice. The allergy must be towards something you could reasonably encounter within a lifetime.

objects.title: Ultimate Talent
objects.text: Choose a skill or trait. You gain superhuman talent in it, able to progress and improve it at a speed and in ways anyone else simply couldn't. This bonus is weakened as the talent and its applicability is broadened.

objects.title: Gemstone
objects.text:
You are a Gemstone esper, someone with a personal reality strong enough to perform supernatural feats instinctually. 
You may choose to have any power with this ability, although the more restricted the power is the stronger it will be. 
Your powers start out average in strength (around Level 3), but can grow through usage and training. As an esper, your abilities naturally interfere with magic, and attempting to use magic will typically backfire.

objects.title: Spark
objects.text:
You become a strong Spark, in the Girl Genius definition of the term. This means that your scientific abilities become massively better, improving the speed, efficiency and overall quality of your inventions and inventing process by a big amount.
In addition, you have an aura of charisma which will drive people to assist you when you're in the process of invention. 
However, this also comes with a form of madness, driving you to act like a stereotypical mad scientist, and the compulsion only grows stronger as you draw on this power more. This effect can be resisted, but it's quite difficult.

objects.title: Prescience
objects.text: You gain prescience, as it's defined in Dune. This grants you expanded awareness, giving you knowledge of the past, present and future, although without training or amplifiers the effect will be weak and hard to control.

objects.title: Inspiration
objects.text:
You become a Genius, in the World of Darkness sense of the term. This means that your ability to create is increased drastically, making you able to invent devices which can blatantly violate physics simply by virtue of you having made them, and at a far higher quality than otherwise possible. 
However, this becomes the only form of creation you may do, and the things you make will experience catastrophic failures if observed too closely by or used by anyone else. In addition, your attempts to communicate scientific concepts to others becomes impossible, with them just hearing technobabble.

objects.title: Technomancer
objects.text:
You are a technomancer, someone capable of manipulating technology as an act of will. They may create sprites, forms of sentient programs, and execute complex forms, which are essentially "spells" applied to technology. 
You start out with a high Resonance and an instinct that lets you avoid the pitfalls starting technomancers may face, but beyond that you'll need to practice on your own. 
A technomancer will lose Resonance if they modify their body with foreign influences, like cybernetics. It's uncertain if technomancers are magical or scientific.

objects.title: Force-Sensitive
objects.text:
You are a Force-sensitive, meaning you have a stronger-than-normal connection to the Force. Benefits of this, even without training, include increased luck and intuition, better affinity with animals, better affinity with weather, and increased physical abilities. 
With training this can become true superpowers, allowing for a variety of psychic techniques.

objects.title: Tech Tree
objects.text:
You have access to a tech tree, a supernatural construct representing your understanding of science. It starts out filled to the level of your current understanding in all areas, and can be improved with Research Points. 
RP may be gained through learning of any sort, with more RP gained the more you learn. You may spend RP on tech nodes, granting you knowledge of that tech downloaded into your mind directly. If you learn information a tech node would provide, it'll cost less RP, eventually being free if you learn everything it'd give.

objects.title: Inventory
objects.text:
You have access to an infinite pocket dimension, which you may store any item you can pick up in. The items are frozen in time while inside the dimension, and you may summon them to your hands at will. 
You have an instinctive sense of what's in your pocket dimension at all times. You may not store anything sentient in the pocket dimension.

objects.title: Pause Mechanic
objects.text: At will, you may slow down time, as slow as you want and for as long as you want, even down to indefinite freezing if desired. However, your body is also slowed the same as the rest of time is, meaning only your mind retains normal speed.

objects.title: Collective Unconscious
objects.text:
You have some form of access to the world's Collective Unconscious, which is a realm formed from the cognition of all sapients within an area, such as Mementos or the Midnight Channel. 
The exact form of the realm will depend upon your desires, how you view the world, and the nature of where you are. Regardless of what form it takes it will have traits which are useful to you in some way, you'll have a method of entering it which is unique to you, and you'll meet any necessary criteria needed to awaken a Persona in this realm. You are not guaranteed to be a Wild Card.

objects.title: Hive Mind
objects.text:
You can split yourself, creating a perfect copy. The copy is completely identical to you, aside from not possessing this ability, and you may not make a new copy while the old one persists.
You and the copy share a hive mind. If you die while your copy is still alive, your copy will gain this ability and become the new "original".

objects.title: Mind Hive
objects.text:
You have a mental companion, a second personality of full sapience, within your mind. You may design their personality however you like when you select this option, and they will possess all of your knowledge and skills, as well as any mental powers you have. For the purpose of effects which require it, they are a separate, real person. 
You can allow them to control parts of your body, activate mental-triggered effects you have access to, or anything along those lines. They will always remain loyal to you.

objects.title: S.P.E.C.I.A.L.ist
objects.text: You may reallocate your stats, as defined by the S.P.E.C.I.A.L. system: Strength, Perception, Endurance, Charisma, Intelligence, and Luck. When you do so, you gain 5 points you may freely distribute across your stats. This is a one-time-use ability.

objects.title: Observe
objects.text: You gain the Observe skill, a special ability that gives you information. By default it requires you look at the target and say "Observe" (this may be done under your breath), and will give surface-level information. However, it levels up with use, like a skill in a video game, increasing in information quality with each level. When it reaches certain levels, you will be able to give it one of several upgrades, which will change depending on how you use it and your general desires.

objects.title: Quirk
objects.text: You have a Quirk, a form of biological mutation which is, in effect, a superpower. You may choose to have any sort of Quirk this way, although the stronger and more versatile your Quirk is the more downsides it'll have to compensate. Regardless of your selection, your Quirk is a part of your body, and can be trained or improved like such.

objects.title: Hidden Talents
objects.text: You gain a subtle psychic ability of some sort. This power can be of any type, but it must be weak enough that someone without full knowledge could dismiss it as coincidence. With practice, you can gain better control over this ability, but it will never grow stronger on its own.

objects.title: Protocols
objects.text: You gain the ability to access the "source code" of your mind, allowing you to recode or add code to it as you see fit. You may freely choose what programming language your mind is in, and there's an extensive set of different systems in place to ensure you can swiftly undo changes to your mind in the case of a catstrophic error.

objects.title: Heart of Iron
objects.text: Your body, instead of being what it normally would be, is a robot body. Any purchased option which would lose effectiveness from this change is altered so it doesn't. Your robot body, by default, is roughly equivalent in capability to how you would be without this power (altered to account for the benefits and downsides of being a technological being), but it can be upgraded.

objects.title: Psychic
objects.text: You are a psychic, by the Pokemon definition. This means you have natural-born psychic abilities which have a variety of uses, such as telekinesis, telepathy, precognition, teleportation, mind control, and more. You start out weak, but can grow stronger over time and through training.
